proaches along three principal themes: What is authentic language? Who is an authentic speaker? How is authenticity achieved? The volume responds to these questions by bringing together scholars working in a range of contexts, including with language learners in the classroom and in residence or study abroad, with a variety of second or additional languages: Chinese, English, French, German, Japanese and Spanish. Contributions focus on authenticity as it relates to patterns of language and meaning, and to agency, identity and culture, and serve as an opening to an extended conversation about the nature of authenticity and its development in L2 contexts. This volume is relevant for students and scholars interested in learning about or investigating questions of authenticity and interaction in a wide range of language learning contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aApplied linguistics. 0aCommunicative competencexEvaluation. 0aInterlanguage (Language learning) 0aInterlanguage (Language learning). 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aSecond language acquisitionxStudy and teaching. 0aSocial interaction. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aSLA.  aauthentic language.  aauthentic speaker.  aauthenticity.  aforeign language pedagogy.  alanguage acquistion.  alanguage and authenticity.  alanguage and interaction.  alanguage-in-use.  anative-speaker.  asecond language acquisition.  asecond language pragmatics.  astudy abroad.1 aBurch, Alfred Rue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCompernolle, Rémi A. van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiao, Wenhao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernández, Julieta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca